uals."By rethinking the established relation between politics and political theory, Honig argues that political theorists of opposing positions often treat political theory less as an exploration of politics than as a series of devices for its displacement. She characterizes Kant, Rawls, and Sandel as virtue theorists of politics, arguing that they rely on principles of right, rationality, community, and law to protect their political theories from the conflict and uncertainty of political reality. Drawing on Nietzsche and Arendt as well as Machiavelli and Derrida, Honig instead explores an alternative politics of virtú, which treats the disruptions of political order as valued sites of democratic freedom and individuality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aDemocracy. 0aLiberalism. 0aPolitical sciencexPhilosophy. 0aPolitical science. 4aLegal History & Studies. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh  aagonism, antagonism, Arendt and political theory, liberal communitarian debate, Nietzsche and political theory, Kant and political theory, democratic theory.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311075183340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150176845340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501768453423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501768453/original  a978-3-11-075183-3  Cornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK